      "content": "hey, i'm working on a physics engine and i need to implement a spatial partitioning system, specifically an AABB tree. the goal is to take a list of 3D bounding boxes and return a list of all pairs that are colliding. \n\nthe implementation needs to be efficient because we're going to have hundreds of these objects. i can't just use a nested loop (O(n^2)) because the frame budget is too tight. can you write a class for this?\n\nhere is the test data i'm using to verify the collision pairs. i need the code to pass these assertions:\n\n```python\ntest_boxes = [\n    {\"id\": 0, \"min\": (0, 0, 0), \"max\": (1, 1, 1)},\n    {\"id\": 1, \"min\": (0.5, 0.5, 0.5), \"max\": (1.5, 1.5, 1.5)},\n    {\"id\": 2, \"min\": (10, 10, 10), \"max\": (11, 11, 11)},\n    {\"id\": 3, \"min\": (0.2, 0.2, 0.2), \"max\": (0.8, 0.8, 0.8)},\n    {\"id\": 4, \"min\": (5, 5, 5), \"max\": (6, 6, 6)},\n    {\"id\": 5, \"min\": (0.7, 0.7, 0.7), \"max\": (1.2, 1.2, 1.2)}\n]\n\n# Expected colliding pairs (by id)\nexpected_collisions = [(0, 1), (0, 3), (0, 5), (1, 3), (1, 5), (3, 5)]\n\ndef test_aabb_tree(tree_instance, boxes):\n    results = tree_instance.get_collision_pairs(boxes)\n    # Sort for comparison\n    results = sorted([tuple(sorted(p)) for p in results])\n    expected = sorted([tuple(sorted(p)) for p in expected_collisions])\n    assert results == expected, f\"Expected {expected}, but got {results}\"\n```\ncan you implement the `AABBTree` class?",
